        title: 'Legacy and the Cross-Franchise Idea',
        html: '<p>Captain N\'s most enduring contribution to Nintendo\'s cultural history is the idea it planted: that game characters from different franchises could coexist in a shared universe and that such crossovers generated audience excitement beyond what any individual franchise could produce. Nintendo would not officially pursue this idea until Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 64 in 1999, a decade after the show premiered, but the audience appetite that Captain N had demonstrated was real and persistent. The show\'s fan community remained active long after cancellation, and the cross-franchise character interaction it pioneered became a fundamental design element of one of Nintendo\'s most successful modern franchise properties.</p><p>The show ran for three seasons and fifty-three episodes, declining in ambition and production quality as the licence fees for non-Nintendo characters became more difficult to sustain. By the third season, Mega Man and Simon Belmont had been reduced to minor supporting roles, and the series was focusing more exclusively on Nintendo\'s own first-party characters. The final season aired in 1991, the same year that Super Nintendo launched in North America, and the NES era that Captain N had celebrated was already giving way to the next generation of hardware. The show exists now as a vivid document of a specific moment in gaming culture — when the NES library was the entirety of the mainstream gaming imagination.</p>',
